In .NET 10 (starting with .NET 9 SR10+), `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was deprecated on Android because the underlying `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` flag was removed by Google.

The recommended replacement is to use **`KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`** (enabled by default) or handle it manually with **edge-to-edge / WindowInsets**.

## Quick fix — rely on the built-in auto-scroll

.NET MAUI 10 enables `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` by default. If it's not working for you, make sure you haven't disabled it:

```csharp
// In MauiProgram.cs – do NOT add this line (it disables the feature):
// builder.ConfigureKeyboardAutoManagerScroll(false);
```

If your layout is interfering, wrap your page content in a `ScrollView` or ensure the input `Entry`/`Editor` is inside one.

## If you need manual control (edge-to-edge approach)

```csharp
// In your platform Android MainActivity or handler:
#if ANDROID
using AndroidX.Core.View;

WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);

ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window.DecorView, (view, insets) =>
{
    var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
    // imeInsets.Bottom gives keyboard height in px
    // Adjust your bottom padding/margin accordingly
    return insets;
});
#endif
```

Then bind the bottom padding of your input bar to the IME inset height.

## TL;DR

| .NET 9 | .NET 10 |
|--------|---------|
| `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` | `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (default) |

Remove any old `Resize` mode calls and let the default behavior handle it. If layout issues persist, ensure your input view is focusable inside a `ScrollView`.
